(lo. Intermediate between Plautus and Terence stands Statius Caecilius, an Insubrian Gaul, who was brought as a prisoner of war to Rome and there liberated. Hc became an intimate friend of the poet Ennius whom he is said to have survived by only a year. Only fragments of his work are extant, but ancient critics ranked him high in the order of merit¹ Volcatius SedigituS, indeed, sets him first in his canon, while iu Horacc's day Caecilius and Terence were put ou epar,—

Viucere Caecilius gravitate, Terentius arte (Epist. 2. 1. 69).

As compared with Plautus, Caecilius evidently adhered more closely to his Greek models. An indication of this is the fact that of the forty titlcs of his plays known to us, a large majority are Greek, in the Terentian manner. Some titles are given both iu Latin and Greek, while only a few, following the Plautine custom, are Latin only. To the con· struction of the plot Caecilius paid great attention and with marked success² We are told, too, that he worked upon the feelings with sentimental soenes, and in both of these respects we find Terence following in his footsteps. The style of Caecilius, however, unlike that of Terence, was much criticised by Cicero³
